apitalism. She argues that both narratives, that of China's victory and the racist depictions of its culpability, do not address—and even aggravate—these larger forces that degrade the environment and increase the human-wildlife interface through which novel pathogens spill over into humans and may rapidly expand into global pandemics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 0aCOVID-19 (Disease)xGovernment policyzChina. 0aCOVID-19 (Disease)zChina. 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-zChina. 0aCapitalismxHealth aspectszChina. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Disease & Health Issues.2bisacsh  aBiosecurity.  aCOVID-19.  aCapitalism.  aChina.  aGlobal Health.  aGlobalization.  aModernization.  aPandemics.  aPublic Health.  aZoonosis.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073914540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363018540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503630185423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503630185/original  a978-3-11-073914-5  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles